ANAEMIA
Definition:
It is a clinical condition characterised by reduced haemoglobin concentration according to the age and sex
of the individual.
[Lecture of MMC]
Classification:
Morphological (Depending on MCV and MCHC):
A. Normocytic normochromic anaemia (normal MCV and MCHC):
1. Haemorrhage
2. Aplastic anaemia
3. Anaemia of chronic disease: e.g.CKD, connective tissue diseases
4. Malignancy
B. Microcytic hypochromic anaemia (low MCV < 76 fl, low MCHC < 30 g/dL):
1. Iron deficiency anaemia (IDA)
2. Thalassaemia
3. Sideroblastic anaemia
C. Macrocytic anaemia (high MCV > 96 fL):
1. Aaemia due to Vit B12 and folic acid deficiency
2. Alcoholism
3. Hypothyroidism
Normal Hb level:
Male: 13-18 gm/dl
Female: 11.5-16.5 gm/dl
Where we look anemia?
1. Lower palpebral conjunctiva
2. Dorsal surface of tongue (tongue is smooth and loss of papilla )
3. Palm and sole of feet
4. Whole body
How will you say your finding?
Patient is mildly /moderately / severely anemic
In which condition Hb level is 100% and ESR `0’?
Polycythemia
What are the clinical features of anaemia?
Non-specific symptoms:
1. Tiredness
2. Lightheadedness
3. Breathlessness
4. Development/worsening of ischaemic symptoms, e.g. angina or claudication
Non-specific signs:
1. Mucous membrane pallor
2. Tachypnoea
3. Raised jugular venous pressure
4. Tachycardia
5. Flow murmurs
6. Ankle oedema
7. Postural hypotension
[Davidson’s-23
rd
-913]
8
Types of breath sound: 3 types-
1. Vesicular: Normal breath sound
2. Bronchial
3. Vesicular with prolonged expiration
Vesicular breath sound:
ü Inspiration is louder & longer, expiration is shorter
ü No gap between inspiration and expiration
Figure: Diagrammatic representation of breath sounds: A: Vesicular; B: Bronchial.
Cause of diminished breath sound:
Reduced conduction:
1. Obesity/ thick chest wall
2. Pleural effusion or thickening
3. Pneumothorax
Reduced airflow:
1. Localized: Collapse
2. Generalized: COPD
[Macleod’s-13rd-154]
Bronchial breath sound: 2 phases, expiratory > inspiratory phase and gap between inspiratory and expiratory
phases
Common causes:
1. Consolidation
2. Collapse (Peripheral/ with patent bronchus)
3. Fibrosis
4. Cavitations
5. Normally: Over trachea, larynx (In midline)
Why bronchial breath sound is present above the level of pleural effusion?
Effusion compresses the lower lung alveoli and brings the patent bronchus of upper lung near the chest
Vesicular with prolonged expiration:
ü Inspiration is shorter, expiration is longer
ü No gap between inspiration and expiration
Common causes:
1. COPD
2. Bronchial asthma

What is your Dx?
My diagnosis is mitral stenosis
Presentation: Mitral stenosis with pulmonary hypertension:
Examination of precordium of this patient reveals that there is no scar mark, visible cardiac pulsation present at
mitral area. Apex beat in left 5
th
ICS 9cm from midline, tapping in nature. Left parasternal heave, thrill and palpable
P2 present.
On auscultation, 1
st
heart sound is loud in all areas, more in mitral area but 2
nd
heart sound is normal in all areas.
There is opening snap. In early diastole (May be absent too) followed by mid diastolic murmur in mitral area which
is low pitched, localized, rough, rumbling, best heard with bell of the stethoscope in left lateral position in breath
hold after expiration with presystolic accentuation (Mention if present). Base of the lung fields are clear.
What is your Dx?
My diagnosis is mitral stenosis with pulmonary hypertension
Why do you say pulmonary HTN?
1. Left parasternal heave and thrill
2. Palpable P2
3. Loud pulmonary component of S2
What are the features of pulmonary hypertension?
1. Left parasternal heave and thrill
2. Palpable P2
3. Loud pulmonary component of S2
4. Raised JVP with systolic v wave
5. Pulmonary congestion
6. Peripheral oedema
What are the DDs of MS? / What are other causes of mid diastolic murmurs (MDMs)?
1. Left atrial myxoma (Physical signs and murmur change with posture. H/O fever, myalgia, arthralgia,
weight loss, skin rash)
2. Ball valve thrombus in left atrium
3. Severe MR (!Flow through mitral valve causes MDM)
What is the most common cause of mitral stenosis?
Chronic rheumatic heart disease (almost always)
What are the auscultatory findings of MS?
Loud S1, opening snap and MDM with presystolic accentuation
Describe the murmur of MS?
Low pitched, localized, rough rumbling, mid diastolic murmur in mitral area, best heard with bell of
stethoscope in breath hold after expiration
When 1
st
heart sound will be soft and opening snap will be lost?
When mitral valve is calcified (Not a marker of severity)

EXAMINATION OF KNEE JOINT
Examination of knee joint consists of:
1. Look (Inspection)
2. Feel (Palpation)
3. Move (Movement)
Sequence of examination:
Step-A:
1.
!পেশে%র ডান পােশ দঁ াড়ান

4. Proper positioning: Supine position.
5. Proper exposure: Both knee joints including lower 2/3 of thigh
Step-B: Look
A. Look: Look for the following:
1. Any swelling, redness, scar, sinus, and any postural deformity genu valgum (knock-knee) or genu varum
(bowlegs).
2. Any wasting or flexor deformity: If wasting is present, measure the thigh girth in both legs at a selected
distance (say 20 or 10 cm) above a defined fixed bony landmark - the tibial tuberosity.
3. Popliteal fossa: For baker cyst.
**Though it is the part of look /inspection please do it at end of all examination of knee only if patient is
able to stand
Step-C: Feel
1. Temperature
2. Tenderness
3. Synovitis and Synovial thickening (Boggy feeling in suprapatellar area)
4. The patellar tap
5. Bulging or ripple test
6. Feel the popliteal fossa for any swelling

GRAVES’ DISEASE
Common instruction: Look at the face and do the relevant
Steps of examination:
Examination of thyroid gland
¯
‘Sir, I want to do some relevant examination to see the thyroid status of this patient’
¯
Examine the relevant of thyroid/examination of thyroid status.
Description after examination:
Examination of thyroid gland of this patient reveals that thyroid gland is diffusely enlarged 5 cm X 4 cm,
non-tender, firm /soft / hard in consistency, freely mobile, bruit present, no retrosternal extension, no palpable
lymph node and carotid pulse is present.
Hyperthyroid state is present is evidenced warm sweaty palms, tremor of outstretched hands, pulse is 110 / min
regular, exophthalmos, lid lag and lid retraction, ankle jerk is exaggerated, proximal myopathy and pretibial
myxedema present (Mention the positive findings for your patient only).
How will you diagnose Graves’s disease?
Most commonly affects women aged 30–50 years. By triad of
1. Exophthalmos
2. Diffuse goiter
3. Dermopathy (Pretibial myxedema)
What type of disease is it? Which antibody is produced?
ü Autoimmune disease
ü IgG type antibody (Called Thyroid-stimulating immunoglobulins or TSH receptor antibodies (TRAb))
[Davidson’s-23
rd
-643]
Against which receptor does it work?
TSH receptor
[Davidson’s-23
rd
-643]
What thyroid abnormalities may occur in Graves’ disease?
1. Hyperthyroidism: When antibody stimulates TSH receptor
2. Hypothyroidism: When antibody inhibits TSH receptor
3. Euthyroidism: When neither stimulates nor inhibits
[Davidson’s-23
rd
-643-44]
How will you investigate and treat?
Investigations: TSH, TRAb
Rx: Same as hyperthyroidism
[Davidson’s-23
rd
-643-44]
Name some thyroid malignancy.
1. Papillary carcinoma (Most common)
2. Follicular carcinoma
3. Medullary cell carcinoma
4. Anaplastic carcinoma
5. Lymphoma
[Davidson’s-23
rd
-649]
